• Business Understanding
  • Data Understanding
  • Data Preparation
  • Modeling
  • Evaluation
  • Deployment

• Examine the collected data.
  • Identify any data quality issues, missing values, or outliers. 
  • Explore Statistical summaries and visualization to grasp the overall characteristics of the data.

• Separating numerical and categorical features provides a clear overview of the types of data we're dealing with.
  • Numerical and categorical data require different preprocessing steps.

• Number of rows with missing relatively small.
  • Don't significantly affect the size of the dataset.

• High missing ratio
  • Might not provide any insight for analysis

• If the missing are relatively few and appear across the dataset, filling with fixed value might not affect the overall distribution. 
  • Such as 0, 999, -1 and etc.
  • Data collection errors, or missing random.

• Preserving Data Distribution
  • Minimal impact on Data Structure
  • Mean, Median, and Mode

• Transforming categorical data into numerical values.
  • Such as One-Hot Encoding, Ordinal Encoding, Binary Encoding, etc.

• Use Machine Learning model to predict missing values based on other features
  • Complex missing pattern
  • Such as regression, decision trees

• Ensure that features are on the same scale. 
  • Depend on the characteristics of the dataset.
  • Such as Standard Scaling, Min-Max Scaling

• If we have domain or business expertise, some outliers are valid data points and can give valuable insights. 
  • In some case, keeping outliers might not negatively impact model performance.

• If we believe outliers are due to data entry errors or noise that are likely to negatively impact the analysis, replacing outliers is worth to try.
  • Such as Mean, Median.
  • Remain the overall distribution.

• If the model are highly sensitive to outliers like linear regression, dropping might be a better choice.
  • Outliers could significantly affect the scaling process, removing could lead to better scaled distribution.
